The following Rust function performs a depth-first traversal of a binary tree using recursion. Each node contains an integer value and optional left and right children wrapped in Box pointers. The function accepts a reference to an Option<Box<Node>> and returns the sum of all values. At each call, it pattern matches on the node: if None, it returns zero; if Some, it adds the current value to recursive calls on the left and right subtrees. Because Box owns its data on the heap, recursion consumes stack frames proportional to tree height. For deeply unbalanced trees, an explicit stack may be preferable to avoid overflow. The borrow checker ensures that shared references remain valid throughout the traversal, preventing use-after-free errors without a garbage collector.

fn sum_tree(node: &Option<Box<TreeNode>>) -> i32 {
    match node {
        None => 0,
        Some(n) => n.val + sum_tree(&n.left) + sum_tree(&n.right),
    }
}
